tests.commentary: If x is -Infinity, Math.cos(x) is NaN
tests.description: Checking if Math.cos(-Infinity) is NaN

tests.commentary: Cosine is a periodic function with period 2*PI
tests.description: Checking if Math.cos(x) equals to Math.cos(x+n*2*Math.PI) with precision 0.000000000003, where n is an integer from 1 to 100 and x is one of 10 float point values from -Math.PI to +Math.PI

tests.commentary: Math.cos it is recommended that implementations use the approximation algorithms for IEEE 754 arithmetic contained in fdlibm
tests.description: Checking if Math.cos is approximately equals to its mathematical values on the set of 64 argument values; all the sample values is calculated with LibC

tests.commentary: If x is NaN, Math.exp(x) is NaN
tests.description: Checking if Math.exp(NaN) is NaN

tests.commentary: If x is +0, Math.exp(x) is 1
tests.description: Checking if Math.exp(+0) is 1

tests.commentary: If x is -0, Math.exp(x) is 1
tests.description: Checking if Math.exp(-0) is 1

tests.commentary: If x is +Infinity, Math.exp(x) is +Ifinity
tests.description: Checking if Math.exp(+Infinity) is +Ifinity

tests.commentary: If x is -Infinity, Math.exp(x) is +0
tests.description: Checking if Math.exp(-Infinity) is +0

tests.commentary: Math.exp, recommended that implementations use the approximation algorithms for IEEE 754 arithmetic contained in fdlibm
tests.description: Checking if Math.exp is approximately equals to its mathematical values on the set of 64 argument values; all the sample values is calculated with LibC

tests.commentary: If x is NaN, Math.floor(x) is NaN
tests.description: Checking if Math.floor(NaN) is NaN

tests.commentary: If x is +0, Math.floor(x) is +0
tests.description: Checking if Math.floor(x) is +0, where x is +0

tests.commentary: If x is -0, Math.floor(x) is -0
tests.description: Checking if Math.floor(x) is -0, where x is -0

tests.commentary: If x is +Infinity, Math.floor(x) is +Infinity

tests.commentary: If x is -Infinity, Math.floor(x) is -Infinity
tests.description: Checking if Math.floor(x) is -Infinity, where x is -Infinity

tests.commentary: If x is greater than 0 but less than 1, Math.floor(x) is +0
